recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 the root is in the middle. The left subtree is traversed first, then the root, and finally the right subtree.

recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 a traversal that visits the left branch first, then the parent node, then the right branch, recursively.

recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 Inorder traversal visits the left branch of a node (all the way to it's deepest left-most leaf) before visiting the node itself. After visiting the entire left branch and the node, it visits the node's right branch following the same pattern of left child, node, right child.

recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 left middle right

recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 You traverse all the nodes to the left, then visit the root, then traverse all the nodes on the right.

recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 you would go to the furthest down left most node, then to the root then to the right (if left and right exist) then you would return one node previous and do the same until you reached the root, then go to the furthest down left most node on the right side of the root and continue this process

recent_25_results.question: 10.6 What is the inorder traversal of a binary tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.6 it means that you traverse one subtree of a node, then look at the node itself before traversing the other subtree of the node

recent_25_results.question: 10.7 How many comparisons does it take to find an element in a binary search tree?
recent_25_results.student_answer: 10.7 This is on the runtime order of log(n) where n is the number of nodes in the binary tree.
